  <section>
    <h2>Modules and Classes</h2>
    <p>
      Ruby is object-oriented. Classes define objects, and modules provide reusable code that can be 
      mixed into classes. <code>include</code> adds module methods as instance methods, while 
      <code>extend</code> adds them as class methods.
    </p>
    
    <pre><code># Module with methods
module AddOrSub
  def addition(x, y)
    x + y
  end
  
  def subtraction(x, y)
    x - y
  end
end

module Modulus
  def mod(x, y)
    x % y
  end
end

# Class using modules
class Student
  include Modulus          # Instance methods
  extend AddOrSub          # Class methods
  
  attr_accessor :name, :age
  
  def initialize(name, age)
    @name = name
    @age = age
  end
end

# Using class methods (extend)
puts Student.addition(5, 5)
puts Student.subtraction(10, 5)

# Using instance methods (include)
student = Student.new("Alice", 20)
puts student.mod(19, 4)</code></pre>
